{{Refimprove|date=July 2014}}
'''Volturnalia''' was the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[festival]]<ref>http://www.akademiai.com/content/rq3800r1j56p82q8/</ref> on [[August 27]] dedicated to [[Volturnus]], 'god of the waters,' god of fountains. Volturnus was a tribal river god who later was identified as god of the [[Tiber]] river. The [[Volturno]] River, in southern Italy, is named for him.  Volturnus was the father of the goddess Juturna, who was first identified with a spring in [[Latium]] near the [[Numicus]] River and later with a pool near the [[Temple of Vesta]] in the Forum of Rome. They were both honored on this day with feasting, wine-drinking, and games.

